dogfood-skill-testing
=====================

Original design — not a port
-----------------------------

This skill is an **original design** authored for monkey-skills.
It is **not** a port, fork, or code-level adaptation of any existing
skill. No third-party source code, prompt text, or bundled file is
incorporated.

The skill applies the "dogfood" exploratory-QA *pattern* — give a
fresh agent a target, let it explore to surface unanticipated
defects, and emit a structured findings report with reproduction
evidence — to a different substrate: testing a **skill-in-development**
(its triggers, workflow, and output quality via fresh subagents)
rather than a web application. The defect-taxonomy and report-template
*content* are written for the skill-testing domain; only the generic
shapes (severity × category; metadata → summary → per-finding blocks)
are conventional QA structure, not borrowed expression.

Inspiration acknowledged
------------------------

1. vercel-labs — `agent-browser` `dogfood` skill
   (Apache-2.0, Copyright 2025 Vercel Inc.,
   https://github.com/vercel-labs/agent-browser)
   The exploratory-dogfood framing — systematic exploration →
   document-on-discovery → reproduction evidence → structured report,
   and the 6-phase Initialize/Orient/Explore/Document/Wrap-up flow —
   informed this skill's substrate-swapped workflow. No agent-browser
   code or text was copied; the pattern is acknowledged here for
   transparency, not because the license requires it (no Apache-2.0
   "Work" or "Derivative Work" is distributed).

2. Scott Spence — sandboxed skill-activation eval
   (https://scottspence.com/posts/measuring-claude-code-skill-activation-with-sandboxed-evals)
   The real-harness activation-measurement method (temp `.claude/skills/`
   + `claude -p --allowedTools Skill --output-format stream-json`,
   parse `Skill()` events, should-fire / should-NOT-fire corpus)
   informed Probe A. Method acknowledged; no code incorporated.

3. LLM-as-judge practice (Braintrust / Patronus / 電通デジタル et al.)
   and the oracle-problem caution (Konstantinou et al., ICST 2025)
   informed the executor/auditor firewall and judge guardrails in
   Probe B.

